@Misc{LamZE2017,
  author =    "Wing Lam and Sai Zhang and Michael D. Ernst",
  title =     "Accomodating Test Dependence in Testing Algorithms",
  month =     feb,
  year =      2017,
  abstract =
   "When test cases are \emph{independent}, no test affects any other test's
    outcome, and running the tests in any order yields the same test
    outcomes. Many test-reordering techniques, including test prioritization,
    test selection, and test parallelization, assume test independence.
    However, this critical assumption often does not hold in practice, causing
    the test-reordering techniques to produce incorrect suites.
    \par
    This paper first describes an empirical study to assess the impact of test
    dependence on 4 test prioritization, 6 test selection, and 2 test
    parallelization algorithms. Test dependence negatively affects all these
    test-reordering algorithms: the test suites that they produce suffer false
    alarms and missed alarms, both of which are costly in terms of developer
    time or impact the reliability of the software.
    \par
    The paper then presents a new approach that modifies each test-reordering
    algorithm to maintain test dependence. One of its inputs is a set of test
    dependences, which was precomputed from a prior version of the
    software. After the original test prioritization, selection, or
    parallelization algorithm produces a suite, our approach further reorders
    and/or adds tests to the suite to maintain the order required by the test
    dependences. This reduces false positives and false negatives in the final
    test suite.
    \par
    In an experimental evaluation, dependence-aware test-reordering algorithms
    worked as intended: they quickly produced test suites whose outcomes were
    consistent with the original order, even when the original suite contained
    dependent tests.",
  omitfromcv = 1,
  underreview = 1,
  basefilename = "test-dependence",
  category =  "Testing",
  summary =
   "Test-reordering techniques such as prioritization can fail when tests are
    dependent (their outcome depends on their order of execution).  This paper
    gives an algorithm that makes test-reordering techniques correct even in
    the presence of dependence.",
}


